            {
                "s2_paper_id": "69c47630a6da33fa39876312614b576dfa8b4b13",
                "title": "Abstract 13952: Neurodevelopmental Outcomes in Early Adolescence: The Pediatric Heart Network\u2019s Single Ventricle Reconstruction Trial",
                "year": 2023,
                "venue": "Circulation",
                "citation_count": 1,
                "reference_count": 0,
                "abstract": "\n Introduction:\n Neurodevelopmental (ND) and functional impairments for survivors of palliated hypoplastic left heart syndrome (HLHS) are among the most consequential morbidities, resulting in an increased risk of poor school performance and lower reported quality of life. Longitudinal follow-up of those enrolled in the Single Ventricle Reconstruction (SVR) III study provides opportunity to measure important outcomes such as ND, and understand associated risk factors.\n \n \n Goals/Aims:\n Describe and identify predictors of ND outcomes at 10-12 years of age in participants enrolled in SVR.\n \n \n Methods:\n Transplant-free survivors from the SVR III trial were invited to complete in-person ND assessments, including the Wechsler Intelligence Scale for Children-V, Wechsler Individual Achievement Test-III, and the Behavior Rating Inventory of Executive Function (BRIEF). Descriptive and regression analyses were performed.\n \n \n Results:\n Of the 237 enrolled in SVR III, 200 (84%) received a ND assessment. Participants who did vs did not undergo assessment were more likely to be male (63% vs 51%), white (87% vs 76%) and have a higher Child Opportunity Index (61 \u00b126 vs 46 \u00b139). Mean Full Scale IQ for the cohort was almost 1 standard deviation (SD) below the normative mean (88 \u00b118), with 39% >1 and 15% >2 SD below the normative mean. Similar patterns were seen for Reading (38% >1 SD and 16% > 2SD) and Math Composites (38% >1 SD, 19% > 2SD). Executive functions measured with the BRIEF were similarly affected, with 25% to 45% of individuals showing clinically significant (T score >65) Plan/Organization problems on parent and teacher forms, respectively. Measures of socioeconomic status, number of complications, and requirement for a gastrostomy-tube were all independent predictors for multiple ND outcomes.\n \n \n Conclusions:\n In early adolescence, transplant-free survivors of surgical palliation for HLHS show clinically significant ND concerns across multiple domains of functioning. The distribution of outcomes is broad. Our findings support the American Heart Association recommendations for screening and evaluation in middle school to inform interventions that promote academic success and quality of life.\n",
